{
  "doc_id": "37690",
  "text": "On the other hand, lizards could show higher tolerance (sensu Svensson and Rå berg 2010; [CITATION_1] to hemoparasites at high elevations. Hosts in better condition may harbor larger intensities of parasites [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . In our study system, we found that body condition tended (albeit not significantly) to improve with elevation, and lizards in better condition tend to harbor higher loads of hemoparasites, although the trend was inconsistent with elevation. This may be driven by increased food availability at higher elevation (MorenoRueda et al. 2017) . Moreover, lizards suffer less oxidative damage at high altitudes [CITATION_5] , which could improve tolerance to parasites [CITATION_6] . Furthermore, lizards are darker at higher elevations [CITATION_7] , and higher melanization has been related to better tolerance to infections [CITATION_8] .",
